@node "Installation" "Installation"
Installation

With AmigaTNC V1.3 comes an automatic installation script which supports
automatic setup of the following PR programmes :

- Amicom

- AmigaHostPacket

- ProfiPacket

If you own one of these packet radio programmes, the automatic installation
is highly recommended. If you use another packet radio programme you can
use the automatic installation to setup AmigaTNC itself. You'll have to
configure your PR programme by yourself.

Automatic installation
======================

For an automatic installation simply double-click on the supplied
"Install_HD" icon. The Amiga Installer must be available on your harddisk.
Now you'll have to answer some questions depending on your equipment.
If you have very special equipment you'll have the change things like in
the manual installation.


Manual installation
===================

After having checked and extracted the archive, you have to copy AmigaTNC and
the @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} example in a directory on your harddisk or disk. Then
you have to setup your individual @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} using an text editor.

Example for installing AmigaTNC on your Harddisk (DH0:) in Packet directory:

copy AmigaTNC#? dh0:Packet


Having setup the @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} correctly, AmigaTNC is ready for use. You
also can install it into your S:User-Startup in order to run it if you boot
your computer. In this case AmigaTNC will automatically be started and other
stations can use you as an digipeater.


Setting up your packet radio programme

First of all you have to make your programme to use the Hostmode or the
KISS-Mode of a TNC. Having done this, you have to redirect the output of your
programme by replacing the name of the output device from "serial.device" into
"amigatnc.device". (NAME IS CASE SENSITIVE, DON'T USE CAPITAL LETTERS!!!) Now
you have to change the unit of this device, if you installed your AmigaTNC
with a @{"DRIVERUNIT" link "Driver_Unit" 0} different from zero. You also should remove all TNC init
commands of your packet radio programm, which are already in your AmigaTNC
@{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0}, because if you want to change some settings you would have
to change it twice when it's also the configuration file of your packet radio
programme. Now, you can save your configuration on your (hard)disk and try to
use the driver. Sometimes you need to reboot your machine before the new
settings are used.


Starting your packet radio programme

First of all you have to @{"start the AmigaTNC driver" link "WB_Usage" 0}. Then you can start your
programme as you would start it if you had a TNC.


Examples :

  @{"Installation for Amicom" link "Install_AmiCom" 0}
  @{"Installation for AmigaHostPacket4" link "Install_AHP4" 0}
@endnode

@node "Install_AmiCom" "Installation for Amicom"
Installation for AmiCom


Step 1

Copy the AmigaTNC files onto your (hard)disk.


Step 2

Write your own @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} and change the tooltype of the AmigaTNC
driver to your @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0}.


Step 3

Change your konfig.ac to following parameters:
  DRIVER "Host.drv"
  DEVICE "amigatnc.device"
  UNIT 0

Remove all TNC 0 commands which are already set in your AmigaTNC @{"configuration" link "Configuration_file" 0}
@{"file" link "Configuration_file" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Install_AHP4" "Installation for AmigaHostPacket4"
Installation for AmigaHostPacket


Step 1

Copy the AmigaTNC files onto your (hard)disk.


Step 2

Write your own @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} and change the tooltype of the AmigaTNC
driver to your @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0}.


Step 3

Change the tooltypes of AHP4 as following:

Change lines:

  (DEVICE=duart.device)          to    DEVICE=amigatnc.device
  (UNIT=0)                       to    UNIT=0
  TNC0=10                        to    TNC0=0
  TNC2=0                         to    TNC2=10

Now AHP4 should use AmigaTNC. You cannot use TNC0 and TNC1 because the serial
interface is used for the packet radio modem.
@endnode

@node "CLI_Usage" "CLI Usage"
CLI usage

You can start AmigaTNC from the command line interpreter.

The command template is:

COMFIGFILE/A,UNLOAD/S



CONFIGFILE is the filename of the @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} which contents the
settings you want to use for starting/removing AmigaTNC. You only may use one
configuration file at the same call.

UNLOAD removes the declared AmigaTNC unit from memory if possible. You cannot
remove it if the driver is used by another programme or you still do have some
connnects.

Example:

AmigaTNC MyConfig.cfg

Runs AmigaTNC with @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} "MyConfig.cfg".
@endnode

@node "WB_Usage" "WB Usage"
WB usage

If you want to start AmigaTNC from your Workbench, you do have three
possibilities.



Starting AmigaTNC using tooltypes


You can add a CONFIGFILE tooltype to your AmigaTNC main icon. For example:

CONFIGFILE=S:AmigaTNC.cfg




Starting AmigaTNC using Default tool :


You can change the default tool of your configuration file icon to the path of
the AmigaTNC driver.



Starting AmigaTNC using multiple selection:


You can start more than one AmigaTNC unit if you click at the configuration
file icons pressing the shift key and then double clicking on the AmigaTNC
driver icon.





There is no way to unload drivers through workbench.
@endnode

@node "Configuration_file" "Configuration file parameters"
Configuration file

The configuration file consits of several lines. Each line is a special
parameter for AmigaTNC. Some parameters you always need, e.g. type of Modem,
other parameters you can add or leave out.

List of parameters:

  - @{"DRIVERUNIT" link "Driver_Unit" 0}
  - @{"PERMANENTDRIVER" link "Permanent_Driver" 0}               
  - @{"DRIVERMODE" link "Driver_Mode" 0}
  - @{"KISSINIT" link "Kiss_Init" 0}
  - @{"KISSTYPE" link "Kiss_Type" 0}
  - @{"TNCDEVICE" link "TNC_Device" 0}
  - @{"TNCUNIT" link "TNC_Unit" 0}
  - @{"TNCFLAGS" link "TNC_Flags" 0}
  - @{"TNCBAUD" link "TNC_Baud" 0}
  - @{"BUFFERS" link "Buffers" 0}
  - @{"TNCINIT" link "TNC_Init" 0}
  - @{"MODEMBAUD" link "Modem_Baud" 0}
  - @{"SOFTWAREDCD" link "Software_DCD" 0}
  - @{"EXCLUSIVETIMER" link "Exclusive_Timer" 0}
  - @{"MULTIPORT" link Multi_Port}

If some of the needed parameters are not set in the configuration file, you
will get an error. Please read these instructions carefully to setup your
driver correctly.


@{"Example for an configuration file" link "Config_Example" 0}

@{"Setting up TNC parameters" link "TNC_Setup" 0}
@endnode

@node "Driver_Unit" "DRIVERUNIT"
Driver Unit

This parameter is neccessary.

You can choose, which unit of amigatnc.device this driver should use. Under
normal circumstances this should be zero. If you want to hold more than one
driver in memory at the same time, these driver units must be different.
@endnode

@node "Permanent_Driver" "PERMANENTDRIVER"
PERMANENTDRIVER

This parameter is not neccessary.   (Standardmode is permanent)

0:  Not permanent mode

If you load the driver, it will stay in memory but it only will be started if
you start your packet radio programme which uses it. If you leave your packet
radio programme and you don't have any connects, the driver will be
automatically leaved, but it stays in memory until in will be unloaded or
reused.

1: Permanent mode

After loading the driver will be automatically started and will only be
leaved, if it has to be unloaded. Other stations can use you as an digipeater,
connect you, writing messages, even you have left your packet radio programme.
Because of a slow down while receiving packets, you should only use this if
your Amiga is fast enough or you don't mind a speed decrease while receiving a
packet.
@endnode

@node "Driver_Mode" "DRIVERMODE"
DRIVERMODE

This parameter is neccessary.

Here you can select which type of modem/TNC you have.


BAYCOMMODEM

These type of modem uses the serial port for input and output of packet radio
signals. It is the standard type of modem for personal computers, but you can
use it on AMIGA,too. The output quality is better than that of the following
type, because it produces output with a special modem chip. It does not use
the audio output of your computer. You should be able to use a standard packet
radio modem for personal computers on your AMIGA, because I put +12V on the
TXD-line, which is used for voltage supply.

BAYCOMAUD

This type of modem uses the serial port for input and PTT, but it uses the
audio output for output of packet radio signals. Because the signal's quality
of your sound chip is not as high as that of the modem chip, you might get
some problems with some stations. I don't suggest you to use this type of
modem, but if you already have bought one and you don't have enough money the
buy a new one, this should be a solution if your old packet radio programme
crashes to often or you don't like it.

BAYCOMMODEMHALF

Works like BAYCOMMODEM, but it does not supply TXD with +12V. RXD/TXD is not
allocated, so you should be able to use serial port for no handshaking serial
transfer.

BAYCOMAUDIOHALF

Works like BAYCOMAUDIA, but it does not supply TXD with +12V. RXD/TXD is not
allocated, so you should be able to use serial port for no handshaking serial
transfer.

KISSTNC

If you own a TNC which does not support the hostmode but the KISS mode, you
can use AmigaTNC as you would use it if you had a modem. Because the computer
doesn't know wheter the TNC has sent a packet or not, in this mode packets can
be broadcasted which are not neccessary. Never use your TNC in KISS mode if
hostmode is available.
@endnode

@node "Kiss_Init" "KISSINIT"
KISSINIT

Neccessary if DRIVERMODE is KISSTNC

Here you can setup which control sequence AmigaTNC has to send to put your TNC
into KISS mode. Control chars can be replaces by a backslash an the ASCII code
of the control char. You have to look up in your TNC's documentation for
setting up this. If you use the firmware , you have to setup this:
(for example)

KISSTNC \\017\\021\\027@K\\013


Here are the control sequences of some popular TNCs:


TNC2 with The Firmware       : \\017\\021\\027@K\\013

TNC2 with TAPR firmware      : \\003KISS ON\\013RESTART\\013

PK232                        : \\003KISS ON\\013

KAM                          : INTFACE KISS\\013RESET\\013

@endnode

@node "Kiss_Type" "KISSTYPE"
KISSTYPE

Neccessary if DRIVERMODE is KISSTNC

Here you can select the type of KISS mode. There are some extensions of the
KISS mode available.

0 : Auto detection (see notes)

1 : Standard KISS mode

2 : SMACK mode

3 : Flexnet-CRC-KISS


Note : In autodetection mode the extension of the KISS mode is only
       detected if a packet is received. Until this packet arrives it
       is possible that you're unable to send packets.
@endnode

@node "TNC_Device" "TNCDEVICE"
TNCDEVICE

Neccessary if @{"DRIVERMODE" link "Driver_Mode" 0} is KISSTNC.

Here you have to say AmigaTNC, where our TNC is conncted. If you only have one
serial port you have to use the serial device:

TNCDEVICE serial.device
@endnode

@node "TNC_Unit" "TNCUNIT"
TNCUNIT

Neccessary if @{"DRIVERMODE" link "Driver_Mode" 0} is KISSTNC.

Here you have to say AmigaTNC, where our TNC is conncted. If you only have one
serial port you have to set TNCUNIT to zero.
@endnode

@node "TNC_Flags" "TNCFLAGS"
TNCFLAGS

Neccessary if @{"DRIVERMODE" link "Driver_Mode" 0} is KISSTNC.

TNCFLAGS normally is set to zero. If your interface device has to be set to a
special mode while LVO_OpenDevice, you have to change TNCFLAGS.
@endnode

@node "TNC_Baud" "TNCBAUD"
TNCBAUD

Neccessary if @{"DRIVERMODE" link "Driver_Mode" 0} is KISSTNC.

Here you have to set the baud rate you use for your TNC. The baud rate of the
TNC often can be changed by jumpers or switches. If possible you should use at
least 9600.
@endnode

@node "Buffers" "BUFFERS"
BUFFERS

This parameter is not neccessary.         (Standard : 600 buffers)


AmigaTNC has to allocate buffers for incoming packets or packets which you
want to broadcast. Every buffer needs 68 bytes of your memory. As more buffers
you use as more messages / incoming packets can be stored in memory while your
packet radio programme is not load or not able to read out these buffers. You
have to use at least 200 buffers, but if you do have enough memory, you should
use more because if only a few buffers are left, you will not be able to
receive packets in your monitor.
@endnode

@node "TNC_Init" "TNCINIT"
TNCINIT

Parameter not neccessary, can be used several times.


When the driver is launched you can change the default settings by using @{"TNC" link "TNC_Commands" 0}
@{"commands" link "TNC_Commands" 0} which will be internally send to the TNC which is emulated by
AmigaTNC. This settings can be changed by sending @{"TNC commands" link "TNC_Commands" 0} to the driver
by your packet radio programme. It's better to set the TNC parameters in your
AmigaTNC configuration file than set it up when you load your packet radio
programme. If you use @{"permanent mode" link "Permanent_Driver" 0}, you have to setup all your parameters in
your AmigaTNC @{"configuration file" link "Configuration_file" 0} because AmigaTNC has to know your callsign
and other parameters.

The TNCINIT line consists of two parts. First of all you have to say, on which
channel the command has to be send. Then the TNC command is following.

Example:            (changing callsign to AM1GA on all channels)

TNCINIT 0 AM1GA
@endnode

@node "Modem_Baud" "MODEMBAUD"
MODEMBAUD


Parameter not necessary  -  Standard baud rate is 1200


With this parameter you can set the baud rate of a modem driver. Be careful:
Higher baud rates can slow down your computer. It will even stop, if you set
baud too high on slow computers. So be careful.
@endnode

@node "Software_DCD" "SOFTWAREDCD"
SOFTWAREDCD


Parameter not neccessary   -  Standard setting : 0


You can adjust the sensitivity of the internal software DCD (digital carrier
detect) by setting this value. 0 means the internal software DCD is disabled.
This is recommended if you own a modem with hardware DCD or a slow computer
system. If SOFTWAREDCD is set <> 0 software DCD is enabled. Only packets with
the same baud rate will be recognized. A higher value of SOFTWAREDCD means
that DCD is less sesitive. A value between 2 and 6 should be OK.
@endnode


@node "Exclusive_Timer" "EXCLUSIVETIMER"
EXCLUSIVETIMER (EXPERIMENTAL)


Parameter not neccessary   -  Standard setting : 1

0 : The modem driver works in shared timer mode. This means a more linear
    scanning method is used for receiving packets. This method is not yet
    very elaborated. Don't use this mode if you are not forced to use it.
    This mode makes it possible to use a modem driver and a TNC Kiss driver
    at the same time.

1 : The modem driver works in exclusive timer mode. No other AmigaTNC units
    can be used if this driver is running in exclusive mode. The exclusive
    mode works better than the shared mode and uses less CPU time. Use this
    mode if you can.

@endnode

@node "Multi_Port" "MULTIPORT"
MULTIPORT (EXPERIMENTAL)


Parameter not neccessary   -  Standard setting : 0

0 : AmigaTNC works in single port mode. No port information is displayed
    in the monitor and you can only connect on port 1 of your TNC.

1 : AmigaTNC works in multi port mode. The port number is displayed and
    you can connect on all 8 available ports. In the modem drivers the
    ports 2-8 are internal loopback ports which can be used to check
    your packet radio programme.


    NOTE : Multi port support might still incompatible with TNC3S firmware.
           I don't have any information about the details of the multi port
           support of the TNC3S firmware.
@endnode


@node "Config_Example" "Example for an configuration file"
Examples for AmigaTNC configuration files


Configuration file for an permanent baycom modem driver. If you want to use a
BAYCOMAUD modem you have to change DRIVERMODE. Please don't forget to change
your callsign.

  DRIVERUNIT 0
  PERMANENTDRIVER 1
  DRIVERMODE BAYCOMMODEM
  SOFTWAREDCD 4
  TNCINIT 0 A 1
  TNCINIT 0 C CQ
  TNCINIT 0 E 1
  TNCINIT 0 F 750
  TNCINIT 0 I MYCALL
  TNCINIT 0 K 2
  TNCINIT 0 M N
  TNCINIT 0 N 20
  TNCINIT 0 O 4
  TNCINIT 0 P 35
  TNCINIT 0 R 1
  TNCINIT 0 T 20
  TNCINIT 0 U 2 Terminal offline. Pse QRX
  TNCINIT 0 W 10
  TNCINIT 0 X 1
  TNCINIT 0 Y 10
  TNCINIT @D 0
  TNCINIT @I 128
  TNCINIT @U 0
  TNCINIT @V 0
  TNCINIT @T2 225
  TNCINIT @T3 18000


Configuration file example for an non permanent driver where TNC parameters
are set in the startup of your packet programme.

  DRIVERUNIT 0
  PERMANENTDRIVER 0
  DRIVERMODE BAYCOMMODEM


Configuration file example for an "The Firmware KISS TNC". This example is
not very useful because you should use the Hostmode of "The Firmware" if
you can. The TNC is connected to the internal serial interface of the
Amiga (you can change this if you want to)

  DRIVERUNIT 0
  PERMANENTDRIVER 1
  DRIVERMODE KISSTNC
  TNCDEVICE serial.device
  TNCUNIT 0
  TNCFLAGS 0
  TNCBAUD 9600
  KISSINIT \\017\\021\\027@K\\013
  TNCINIT 0 A 1
  TNCINIT 0 C CQ
  TNCINIT 0 E 1
  TNCINIT 0 F 750
  TNCINIT 0 I MYCALL
  TNCINIT 0 K 2
  TNCINIT 0 M N
  TNCINIT 0 N 20
  TNCINIT 0 O 4
  TNCINIT 0 P 35
  TNCINIT 0 R 1
  TNCINIT 0 T 20
  TNCINIT 0 U 2 Terminal offline. Pse QRX
  TNCINIT 0 W 10
  TNCINIT 0 X 1
  TNCINIT 0 Y 10
  TNCINIT @D 0
  TNCINIT @I 128
  TNCINIT @U 0
  TNCINIT @V 0
  TNCINIT @T2 225
  TNCINIT @T3 18000
@endnode

@node "TNC_Setup" "Setting up TNC parameters"
Setting up TNC parameters


You should change your TNC parameters if one of this problems occurs:



If not only one packet is received, one acknowledgement for each packet is
sent.

To fix this problem you should increase the packet response timer (@T2). 225
should be a good value.



The first packet you send cannot be received by other stations

Maybe your TX delay is too short. Try to increase it, but try to keep it as
short as possible.
@endnode

@node "TNC_Commands" "Supported TNC commands"
Supperted TNC commands

A    (auto linefeed - terminal mode)

  0: No linefeed is sent
  1: Linefeed is sent after carriage return


C    (connect)

  no parameters       : Displays the connected station
  call digi1 digi2 .. : Connects a station

  On monitor channel you select the unproto path.


D    (disconnect)

  no parameters. Disconnects a channel. If packets are not yet acknowledged,
  channel will be disconnected if they are all disconnected. If you call the
  disconnect command twice, the disconnect will be immediately. Iff you call
  it three times, the channel will be disconnected without regard of the
  connected station


E    (echo - terminal mode)

  0 : No echo
  1 : Echo 

  If echo is used, all chars received by AmigaTNC will be put back to the
  packet radio programme.


F    (frack time)

  no parameter : ask for current frack time on this channel
  1-15    : frack time in seconds
  16-65535: frack time in 1/100 seconds

  Frack time is the time which will be waited for acknowledgement of the
  other station. If you use digipeaters, frack time will automatically be
  adapeted.


G    (host mode poll command)

  Only used in hostmode. No nearer description


I    (mycall)

   no parameter : Displays current mycall at this channel
   call         : Changes your mycall on this channel (only if not
                  connected)


JHOST

   Jumps into the hostmode or back to terminal mode. No nearer description.


K    (TNC timestamps )

  no parameter : displays timestamp mode and current time
  0            : switches of all timestamps
  1            : timestamps on link messages only
  2            : timestamps on link messages and monitor packets
  hh:mm:ss     : Sets time of TNC clock
  dd.mm.yy     : Sets date of TNC clock and enables dd.mm.yy format
  mm/dd/yy     : Sets date of TNC clock and enables mm/dd/yy format


L    (link status)

  no parameter : displays link status of all channels
  channel      : displays link status of a single channel
  hostmode     : displays link status in a special format


M    (monitor)

  no parameter : displays current monitor mode
  N            : no packets will be monitored
  U            : unnumbered packets will be monitored
  I            : information packets will be monitored
  S            : supervisory packets will be monitored
  C            : packets will be monitored while connect
  + call1 ...  : only packets of these stations will be monitored
  - call1 ...  : packets of this stations will not be monitored

  You cannot combine + and - parameter or N and U,I,S,C parameter.
  All other combinations can be used.


N    (tries)

  no parameter : displays current retries of this channel
  1-255        : number of retries if no answer
  0            : infinite retries (please be careful)


O    (maxframe)

  no parameter : displays current maxframe of this channel
  1-7          : max. number of packets which will be sent at the same time


P    (persistence)

  no parameter : displays current persistence
  0-255        : changes the persistence


QRES (reset)

  no parameter
  resets the internal TNC. All settings well be restored to standard and
  all connects will be lost.


R    (L2 digipeating)

  no parameter : displays wheter digipeating is on or off
  0            : L2 digipeating off
  1            : L2 digipeating on


S    (channel select - terminal mode)

  no parameter : displays selected channel
  0-MaxChannel : Switches to another channel


T    (TX delay)

  no parameter : displays current TX delay
  0-255        : changes TX delay


U    (unattended mode)

  no parameter : displays unattended mode and message
  0            : Turns unattended mode off
  1 <msg>      : Turns unattended mode on & stores <msg> as a message
  2 <msg>      : Sames as 1 but //Q will disconnect

  <msg> can be omitted if message has not to be changed.


V    (version)

  no parameter : displays current version of AX25 protocol


W    (slottime)

  no parameter : displays current slottime
  1-255        : changes slottime


X    (enable PTT)

  no parameter : displays wheter PTT is enabled or not
  0            : disables PTT
  1            : enables PTT


Y    (max. external connects)

  no parameter : displays max. number of connects and current number of
                 connects in parenthesis.
  0-maxchannel : changes max. number of connects


Z    (flow control)

  no parameter : displays current flow control mode
  0            : flow control off / XON/XOFF handshaking off
  1            : flow control on  / XON/XOFF handshaking off
  2            : flow control off / XON/XOFF handshaking on
  3            : flow control on  / XON/XOFF handshaking on


 @B  (free buffers)

  no parameter : displays number of free buffers (each buffer 32 byte)


 @D  (full duplex)

  no parameter : displays whether duplex is on or off
  0            : no duplex
  1            : duplex on  (not supported by modem)


 @I  (information poll)

  no parameter : displays max. paclen of information poll
  0            : information poll off
  1-256        : changes max. paclen of information poll


 @K  (KISS mode)

  no parameter : sets AmigaTNC into KISS mode


 @M  (masking - terminal mode)

  no parameter : displays current masking status
  0            : masking off
  1            : masking on

 @P  (change pid of channel - not implemented in FIRMWARE)

  no parameter : displays current protocol identifier
  0-255        : changes protocol identifier of this channel

 @T2  (timer 2 - packet response timer)

  no parameter : displays packet response time in 1/100 sec
  1-65535      : changes packet response time  (in 1/100 sec)


 @T3  (timer 3 - timeout poll timer)

  no parameter : displays timer 3 timer in 1/100 sec
  1-65535      : changes timer 3 timer (in 1/100 sec)


 @TA  (TX tail)

  no parameter : changes current TX tail
  0-255        : changes TX tail


 @U  (UI poll)

  no parameter : displays current UI poll status
  0            : no UI poll
  1:           : UI poll


 @V  (callcheck)

  no parameter : displays current callcheck status
  0            : callcheck off
  1            : callcheck on
@endnode

